   occur via an intermediate phase (I-phase) which involves oscillations of
   profiles due to ZF and MF competition. The I-phase appears as a
   nonlinear transition wave originating at the edge boundary and
   propagates inward. Locally, I-phase exhibits the characteristics of a
   limit-cycle oscillation. All these observations are consistent with
   recent experimental results. We examine the trigger of the L -> H
   transition, by defining a ratio of the rate of energy transfer from the
   turbulence to the zonal flow to the rate of energy input into the
   turbulence. When the ratio exceeds order unity, ZF shear gains energy,
   and a net decay of the turbulence is possible, thus triggering the L ->
   H transition. Numerical calculations indicate that the L -> H transition
   is triggered by this peak of the normalized ZF shearing. Zonal flows act
   as ``reservoir,{''} in which to store increasing fluctuation energy
   without increasing transport, thus allowing the mean flow shear to
