  url={http://stacks.iop.org/0741-3335/50/043001},
  year={2008},
  abstract={A review of the application of dimensionless parameter
scaling techniques to magnetic fusion experiments is presented. Because
the methods of this type of analysis are not generally known, a detailed
discussion of the basis for these techniques is given, including
examples. The primary applications and successes of these methods in
magnetic fusion research are in the area of transport of energy and
particles across surfaces of constant magnetic flux. The experimental
justification for the use of these techniques to describe transport is
given, and the applications are reviewed. The two key applications of
these techniques, the identification of the underlying physical
mechanisms that cause transport and the projection of the transport in
future devices from present-day experiments, are extensively
discussed. Comparison of the results of dimensionless parameter scaling
experiments with the regression analysis of multi-machine databases
points to limitations in the databases and the analysis of them as the
source of the discrepancies. These discrepancies have significant
implications for the design optimization of tokamaks, which are
discussed here. Finally, the application of dimensionless parameter
scaling techniques to plasma stability, to the boundary region between
closed and open field lines and to divertor operation in the open field
line region are reviewed and discussed.}  }


